01:03.462 --> 01:06.799
Well, wait a second.

01:08.834 --> 01:12.605
My last two chewy candies!
I was looking for those.

01:12.638 --> 01:14.140
We'd give you a lift
back into town,

01:14.173 --> 01:15.575
but Myrna here
has got the croup.

01:17.275 --> 01:18.710
Okay.

01:18.743 --> 01:21.180
Well, I could use the walk.
Gives me time to think.

01:21.212 --> 01:22.848
Well, there's plenty of time
for that around here.

01:22.882 --> 01:24.250
Yes.

01:24.283 --> 01:26.652
You know, if I take
the back way...

01:26.685 --> 01:29.355
Okay, bye bye now.

01:42.367 --> 01:45.271
Paint the sign...

01:45.304 --> 01:46.573
What's next?

01:57.849 --> 02:00.385
We'll be looking
at a mild day and night today

02:00.418 --> 02:02.621
in Southern New Jersey,
with temperatures reaching 70

02:02.655 --> 02:05.457
by the afternoon,
and a low tonight of 55,

02:05.490 --> 02:06.792
which will make it
a nice night

02:06.825 --> 02:09.294
for all you ghosts
and goblins out there.

02:14.766 --> 02:16.868
-Up already.
-Who can sleep?

02:16.901 --> 02:18.537
Did you get the paper?

02:20.772 --> 02:23.643
"Paul Davison,
Lullaby's principal landowner

02:23.675 --> 02:24.843
and dairy farm proprietor..."

02:24.877 --> 02:26.412
Skip to the end.

02:26.444 --> 02:28.580
"Despite a few objections
to the rotolactor,

02:28.614 --> 02:30.449
including mayor Clark Hill..."

02:30.481 --> 02:33.618
"Due to Mr. Davison's
foresight and persistence,

02:33.651 --> 02:36.522
the milk business in Lullaby
might not go sour."

02:39.792 --> 02:41.627
Well, now what's this?

02:41.659 --> 02:45.564
Something for your foresight
and persistence.

02:45.598 --> 02:47.333
What a gal.

02:50.868 --> 02:54.507
I love it.

02:54.539 --> 02:59.211
I've always wanted a toy statue
of the empire state building.

03:05.651 --> 03:07.687
Say, hon, do me a favor

03:07.719 --> 03:10.590
and shine my shoes
for me, will you?

03:10.622 --> 03:12.290
Okay.

03:12.324 --> 03:15.995
You, you're the tops.

03:18.764 --> 03:20.533
Ann, breakfast.

03:20.566 --> 03:22.001
No time. Gotta go.

03:22.033 --> 03:23.635
Please take Ziggy with you.

03:23.669 --> 03:25.304
I'm not his babysitter.

03:25.336 --> 03:27.339
No, you're his cousin.

03:27.372 --> 03:29.341
Second cousin, once removed.

03:29.375 --> 03:31.409
I kinda wish he was removed
from our house.

03:31.443 --> 03:34.247
He's family, Ann, and he's only
been with us a week,

03:34.280 --> 03:35.681
so please be nice.

03:35.713 --> 03:37.515
Come on, Ziggy!

03:37.549 --> 03:39.652
Ziggy, let's go!
You're like molasses.

03:39.685 --> 03:41.954
He's from Poland,
he doesn't speak english.

03:41.986 --> 03:44.389
Ziggy, let's go!
You're like Polish molasses.

03:54.932 --> 03:57.469
Ceremony 4:00!

03:57.502 --> 03:59.037
-Don't forget!
-How could I?

03:59.070 --> 04:00.406
That's all you people
talk about.

04:20.858 --> 04:22.627
Sorry I'm late again, gang.

04:22.661 --> 04:24.797
Guess it's time
for that new alarm clock.

04:30.968 --> 04:34.406
Let's jump right in with...

04:39.110 --> 04:41.447
"I heard the voice
of the lord saying

04:41.480 --> 04:43.081
'whom shall I send
and who will go for us?'

04:43.115 --> 04:45.285
then said I,
'here am I, send me.'"

04:48.454 --> 04:49.788
start with that one?

04:51.523 --> 04:53.026
Maybe another one?

04:54.992 --> 04:57.096
Any requests?

04:57.129 --> 05:00.665
Tomorrow is Halloween.
Do you know what that means?

05:00.699 --> 05:02.435
Candy!

05:02.468 --> 05:06.439
It means, for one night you can
let go of your inhibitions

05:06.471 --> 05:09.308
and become someone
completely different.

05:12.944 --> 05:14.612
What are inhibitions?

05:14.646 --> 05:17.983
Well, they're... they're things
that hold you back.

05:18.016 --> 05:19.752
From what?

05:28.826 --> 05:32.130
Chardy Edwards,
you scared us to death.

05:32.163 --> 05:34.500
Peg, I'm gonna remember
that look on your face forever.

05:34.533 --> 05:35.701
That was hilarious.

05:35.733 --> 05:37.736
I was hoping you'd stop by.

05:37.769 --> 05:39.504
-You must be a mind reader.
-I must be.

05:39.538 --> 05:40.805
You know why?

05:40.838 --> 05:43.408
'Cause I knew
you'd say that.

05:43.442 --> 05:45.110
Stop it, Chardy,
the kids are right there.

05:45.144 --> 05:47.612
Well, they're gonna have
to learn about love

05:47.646 --> 05:49.081
sooner or later.

05:49.113 --> 05:52.685
Peg, I love you so much,
I could explode.

06:14.139 --> 06:16.408
Morning!
Morn...

06:16.442 --> 06:18.843
Hey, good morning, Mr. Mayor.

06:18.877 --> 06:22.014
Nice to see you.
Nice to see you, too.

06:22.047 --> 06:25.551
How are you? Well, I'm just
remarkable, thank you.

06:25.584 --> 06:27.752
<i>Today in war-frightened Europe</i>

06:27.786 --> 06:29.622
<i>German chancellor
Adolf Hitler declared</i>

06:29.654 --> 06:31.556
<i>he would not allow
an alien race</i>

06:31.589 --> 06:34.459
<i>to control
his country's destiny.</i>

06:34.492 --> 06:36.060
That German's
got the whole world

06:36.093 --> 06:37.963
on pins and needles.

06:39.197 --> 06:41.166
Crazier than a rat
in a tin can.

06:41.199 --> 06:44.702
A rat in a tin can with tanks.

06:44.735 --> 06:46.070
And guns.

06:46.103 --> 06:48.574
-Coffee, Mr. Mayor?
-Thank you very much.

06:48.607 --> 06:51.944
Nothing like a piping hot cup
of pepper's famous motor oil.

06:51.976 --> 06:54.479
Here come
the rockefellers.

06:56.882 --> 06:59.617
-Hey, sheriff.
-Mr. davison.

06:59.651 --> 07:02.521
-Hello, Clark.
-Lorraine, good morning.

07:02.553 --> 07:03.521
How are things?

07:03.555 --> 07:05.624
Good, good, good, good.

07:05.656 --> 07:06.625
Busy.
how are you?

07:06.658 --> 07:07.693
A big, big day for Paul.

07:07.725 --> 07:09.161
Sure is, thank you.

07:09.194 --> 07:10.830
You're still reading,
"gone with the wind."

07:10.862 --> 07:12.064
You've been at that
for a couple of weeks.

07:12.096 --> 07:13.832
I'm such a slow reader,

07:13.865 --> 07:16.568
-but thank you for the recommendation.
-Sure, sure.

07:16.601 --> 07:19.537
Such a beautiful love story.
I'm really enjoying it.

07:19.571 --> 07:20.940
Good,
I'm glad you like it.

07:20.973 --> 07:23.843
I... I... I would always
find myself re-reading

07:23.875 --> 07:25.743
-that section where...
-Clark!

07:25.776 --> 07:27.146
Paul.

07:27.178 --> 07:29.681
Say, were you able to get
that sign painted,

07:29.714 --> 07:33.151
"Chosen as the Home
of the Rotolactor?"

07:33.185 --> 07:36.788
I... I... I... thought it was
just "Home of the Rotolactor."

07:36.822 --> 07:38.057
No, it's gotta say,
"Chosen as."

07:38.089 --> 07:40.091
-That's important.
-Okay, then, okay, okay.

07:40.125 --> 07:43.661
And the tablecloths
and apple cider, all set?

07:43.694 --> 07:45.730
-Yep, that's next on my list. Next on my list.
-All right.

07:45.764 --> 07:50.970
Cause this isn't some barbeque or
manure stacking contest, Clark.

07:51.002 --> 07:53.004
It's been a long time
since I've planned

07:53.038 --> 07:55.540
a manure stacking contest.

07:55.574 --> 07:58.644
Clark, listen, I know we've had
our differences about this,

07:58.677 --> 08:01.980
and you're worried first
it's a cow milking machine,

08:02.014 --> 08:04.884
next a factory
and a train station pop up,

08:04.916 --> 08:07.652
and before you know it,
we're a Metropolis,

08:07.685 --> 08:09.187
but, trust me, pal,

08:09.221 --> 08:11.656
change only comes

08:11.689 --> 08:15.995
when you take bold
leaps forward.

08:16.028 --> 08:17.997
You oughta write that
in your little diary.

08:25.603 --> 08:27.305
You really want me...
Okay, yep.

08:27.338 --> 08:30.242
-Change only comes when...
-Yeah, I got it, I got it.

08:30.274 --> 08:32.110
-You take bold...
-I got it. I got it.

08:32.144 --> 08:34.145
-He's got it, Paul.
-All right, good.

08:36.148 --> 08:38.984
Well, you should welcome advice
about taking charge, Clark.

08:39.017 --> 08:41.820
-Yeah, sure.
-I mean, you're the mayor.

08:41.852 --> 08:43.755
It's in the job description.

08:45.356 --> 08:48.059
Thank you for your help, Clark.

08:48.092 --> 08:49.728
Good seeing you.

08:58.370 --> 09:00.105
More coffee, Mr. Mayor?

09:02.740 --> 09:05.877
Reverend Rogers,
Helen and I couldn't find you

09:05.910 --> 09:08.713
after mass last week.
You left so quickly.

09:08.746 --> 09:10.915
I wanted to talk about
my brother Joe's passing.

09:10.948 --> 09:14.652
Have you
learned anything

09:14.686 --> 09:15.988
from this time
of trial, Stan?

09:16.020 --> 09:17.188
You bet.

09:17.221 --> 09:18.624
When a cow kicks you
in the leg,

09:18.657 --> 09:19.959
it don't feel like much.

09:19.991 --> 09:22.226
But if she nails you
just right in the head,

09:22.259 --> 09:24.295
boy, you're done for.

09:24.328 --> 09:26.064
Very spiritual.

09:26.097 --> 09:28.866
No, tell him about
the passage you found.

09:28.899 --> 09:32.236
Yeah, "they are plans
for peace and not disaster,

09:32.269 --> 09:35.640
to give you a future
and a hope."

09:35.673 --> 09:38.110
Exodus chapter eight.
That's one of my favorites.

09:38.143 --> 09:40.812
No, it's from Jeremiah,
chapter 29?

09:40.846 --> 09:43.014
I always get
those two confused.

09:43.048 --> 09:45.618
Well, I'll keep your brother,
Jonathan, in my prayers.

09:45.650 --> 09:48.086
-My brother was Joe.
-I'll pray for them both.

09:58.096 --> 10:00.231
Come on!
We're sitting ducks out here.

10:02.100 --> 10:03.869
-Think he saw us?
-Don't move! Stay down!

10:03.902 --> 10:05.871
Hi, Peter.
How you doing

10:05.903 --> 10:07.005
fine.

10:07.038 --> 10:09.140
Hey, lovebirds,
shut the hell up.

10:09.173 --> 10:11.175
Do you want him to hear us?

10:11.208 --> 10:13.878
Look, my folks said that when
Collins came back from the war.

10:13.912 --> 10:15.346
He was all messed up.

10:15.379 --> 10:17.015
Maybe he blew away
a thousand krauts,

10:17.048 --> 10:18.350
blasting their brains out.

10:18.383 --> 10:20.285
Who knows what he does
in there all day?

10:20.317 --> 10:23.688
Here, throw it.

10:23.721 --> 10:26.191
Why is it warm?

10:26.224 --> 10:28.794
Is this pee?
Gross.

10:28.826 --> 10:30.763
Is it true that Ziggy's
an imbecile in the head

10:30.796 --> 10:32.898
-'cause he never talks?
-You're an imbecile.

10:32.931 --> 10:34.233
He's Polish.

10:34.265 --> 10:36.367
Our family sent him here
'cause of Hitler.

10:36.400 --> 10:38.336
-Ever listen to the radio?
-Okay, here we go.

10:38.370 --> 10:40.272
If he comes out,
don't look him in the eyes.

10:40.304 --> 10:41.373
Just keep moving.

10:46.077 --> 10:47.145
Ew!

10:55.721 --> 10:58.256
These last few years
haven't been easy,

10:58.289 --> 11:02.827
but today we look ahead
at brighter days to come...

11:02.860 --> 11:07.899
Ladies and gentlemen,
I'm proud to present

11:07.932 --> 11:09.301
the rotolactor.

11:12.971 --> 11:15.073
And then I'll say
something like...

11:16.508 --> 11:19.211
This is a modern marvel.

11:19.244 --> 11:24.716
How it can milk
15 cows at once.

11:24.750 --> 11:27.318
And Clark, this is where
you're gonna lead the cows in.

11:27.351 --> 11:28.754
Yeah, okay.

11:30.154 --> 11:32.757
Then I'm gonna tug
on the heartstrings

11:32.791 --> 11:34.326
a little bit.

11:34.359 --> 11:36.929
Our fields are drying up.

11:36.961 --> 11:40.899
You're working your fingers to
the bone, barely getting by.

11:40.932 --> 11:43.302
Events in Europe
are drawing us ever closer

11:43.335 --> 11:45.937
to an inevitable world war.

11:48.005 --> 11:50.775
I say change only comes

11:50.808 --> 11:54.480
when you take
bold leaps forward.

11:56.280 --> 11:59.450
Well, that's it. Now what
do you say we fire this up?

11:59.484 --> 12:00.953
Absolutely.

12:12.798 --> 12:14.767
-And all these buttons...
-Yeah?

12:14.799 --> 12:16.501
Designed and built in Florida.

12:16.534 --> 12:19.203
I think it's the future
in dairy farming.

12:19.236 --> 12:20.905
The fut...

12:25.943 --> 12:29.147
And when the time is...

12:34.186 --> 12:36.889
My God!

12:36.922 --> 12:39.291
-Has it got rotors on it?
-Yeah, get over here!

12:39.323 --> 12:41.492
-Dump it right on there?
-Yeah, get out of the way!

12:41.525 --> 12:42.560
Get out of the way!

12:45.529 --> 12:48.900
I cannot believe it.
This is a disaster.

12:48.933 --> 12:50.336
God!

13:01.111 --> 13:03.248
Chardy!

13:13.258 --> 13:15.160
You're damn right I'm upset.

13:15.192 --> 13:17.261
The whole town
was due to arrive.

13:17.294 --> 13:19.931
I had to cancel
the whole damn ceremony!

13:19.965 --> 13:22.500
No, I couldn't
even start the thing.

13:22.533 --> 13:27.139
There was going to be a
fireworks show, for God's sake!

13:27.172 --> 13:29.007
What do you think?

13:29.039 --> 13:32.577
Look at those
Halloween costumes!

13:32.610 --> 13:34.846
They fit perfectly!

13:34.879 --> 13:38.884
-Kind of itchy.
-You're gonna look great tomorrow.

13:38.917 --> 13:42.187
You are a wonderful
Abraham Lincoln.

13:42.220 --> 13:45.290
And you are the spitting image
of Bette Davis.

13:45.322 --> 13:47.326
Greta garbo!

13:49.894 --> 13:51.963
This...

13:54.164 --> 13:57.403
You'll fix it. You always do.
You'll make it better.

13:59.236 --> 14:02.307
I don't deserve you.

14:02.340 --> 14:04.877
You're the most
beautiful girl in town.

14:04.909 --> 14:06.978
You know that?

14:07.011 --> 14:08.613
In all New Jersey.

